<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Says Malaysia On Right Growth Path </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Friday that his country is on the right
growth path and should achieve a positive growth in the second
quarter of this year as targeted.
</P>
<P>
After contracting about 10 percent in the last quarter of 1998
and 1.3 percent in the first quarter of this year, the positive
growth from the second quarter onwards would make the country more
attractive to long-term investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Launching Intel's latest Premium III processor assembly and
test factor in Bayan Baru, he said the opening of the Intel
facility was a vote of confidence by the American company in the
country's economic climate.
</P>
<P>
He believed that more such serious companies like Intel would
expand or open up their facilities in Malaysia as all indications
point to an all-out recovery of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia had and will always welcome serious long-term
investors to the country as they had made the economy strong and
been providing good job opportunities to its people," Mahathir
said.
</P>
<P>
He said these investors had also helped in the people achieving
greater sophistication, changing from being mere food and drink
manufacturers to high-tech producers just like the foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
"The government and Malaysians greatly appreciate the
confidence shown and the good job done by these serious long-term
investors all these years since the country's independence," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But he said his government would be wary of short-term
investors who came only to make short-term gains and would leave
the country the moment they found that it was not that comfortable
the way they were used to.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia would be able to achieve greater
progress and development if political and economic stability
continued to prevail in the country, and he pledged to continue to
give emphasis to political stability and racial harmony in the
country by ensuring a good and strong government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said Malaysia was confident of achieving the 2020
vision with the continued support of its people and the confidence
of serious long-term foreign investors in the country's ability to
achieve success.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the government also welcomed larger
participation from foreign and local investors in the Multimedia
Super Corridor (MSC) that is being developed in the Kuala Lumpur
area.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was doing everything possible,
especially in making available trained people who have the
capability to absorb high technology knowledge, to serve the MSC
needs.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir reiterated that there would be minimum government
interference in the MSC area of development as required under the
Bill of Guarantee passed by the government.
</P>
<P>
"We will help investors develop in the MSC area. There will be
close interaction between the government and the private sector
here. The government regards the participating private sector as
its partner," he added.
</P>
<P>
Intel, the world's largest computer chip manufacturer, has been
operational in Malaysia since 1972. It has so far invested 1.6
billion U.S. dollars in Malaysia and currently employs more than
8,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
The company expects to invest another 140 million U.S. dollars
in Malaysia this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
