<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 450,000 U.S. College Students Own Guns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half a million of U.S.
college students own guns, according to a Harvard University study
released Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 3.5 percent of college students surveyed said they have a
gun at school, said Dr. Matthew Miller, a researcher at Harvard's
Injury Research and Control Center.
</P>
<P>
Some 14 million students attend colleges in the United States,
so roughly 450,000 students own guns based on that percentage, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that those with alcohol problems are twice
as likely as others to have guns.
</P>
<P>
The study, which appears in the July issue of The Journal of
American College Health, is based on a sample of some 15,000
students at 130 four-year colleges, and did not account for
hunting weapons.
</P>
<P>
The study was based on a 1997 questionnaire filled out
anonymously by students.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that two-thirds of the student gun owners
live off-campus. Although most colleges prohibit guns on campus,
researchers estimate students keep at least 100,000 guns in the
nation's dormitories.
</P>
<P>
Reports say bout 200 million people own guns in the United
States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
