<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM: No Bargain Over PKK Leader Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said Friday there was no bargaining between Turkey and the
European countries over the death sentence of outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) leader Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Turkey's Ankara State Security Court gave Ocalan
death penalty on charges of treason and separatism. Ocalan is
expected to appeal to the court of appeals.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit told reporters that the judicial process against Ocalan
was continuing and he would not comment on an ongoing judicial
case. But he stated that the process would continue in conformity
with the laws of the country.
</P>
<P>
"This process will continue on its due course in accordance
with our conscience and with the needs of Turkey," he said.
</P>
<P>
Western European countries, which are against the death
penalty, called on Turkey not to hang Ocalan after his being
sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that after Turkey's Higher Court of Appeals
completes its work on the Ocalan case, the sentence would be
carried out only after being approved by the parliament and
endorsed by President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan was captured by Turkish special agents in Kenya in
mid-February and has ever since been detained on Imrali Island in
Marmara Sea near western Turkey's province of Bursa where he was
tried on charges of treason.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan-led PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts
between the Turkish security forces and the PKK militants have
claimed over 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
