<HEADLINE> Bomb Alert in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police sent out a bomb
alert Friday in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, three days
after the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) leader Abdullah
Ocalan was sentenced to death for treason.
</P>
<P>
The Anatolia News Agency reported Friday that the Turkish
police have arrested 10 PKK militants in Istanbul after Ocalan's
death verdict was announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, two suspected PKK rebels attacked a coffee
shop in the southeastern province of Elazig with automatic
riffles, killing four civilians and wounding five others including
one police officer.
</P>
<P>
Both assailants were killed by the Turkish security forces.
</P>
<P>
In another attack, some suspected PKK guerrillas killed one
police officer in an armed attack in the eastern province of Van.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces shot dead 22 PKK militants in
recent military operations in the southeastern provinces of
Hakkari, Bingol and Sirnak.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 15-year-old war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey, which has claimed over
37,000 lives since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
