<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Aligned Movement Welcomes G8 Decision on Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
has welcomed a decision by the world's richest nations to ease the
debt burden of developing countries, the South African permanent
mission to the United Nations said in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, NAM wishes to reiterate that only an
outright debt cancellation for the heavily indebted poor countries
without due conditionality is the surest way to secure the
sustainability of the development prospects in these countries,"
South African Press Association quoted the mission as saying in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
At a recent G8 summit in Cologne, Germany, the world's eight
leading industrialized countries agreed to provide a
100-billion-U.S. dollar relief deal to the poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
The G8 comprises Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy,
Japan, the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized that the money was for social programs and
conditional on better government and financial management.
</P>
<P>
NAM said plans by countries to sell their gold reserves for the
purpose of debt relief should be without prejudice to the
interests of gold- producing developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
