<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lukashenko: Belarus Ready to Integrate With West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- President Alexander Lukashenko of
Belarus said Friday that his country is ready "to take the most
resolute steps" toward integration into European structures.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting held in Minsk, the Belarussian capital, to
celebrate the republic's Independence Day and 55 years since the
liberation of Belarus from Nazi invasion, Lukashenko said the
country's Foreign Ministry "has completely failed" in the
establishment of smooth cooperation with the West and European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Because of that failure, Belarus "finds itself outside of
European politics," the Interfax news agency quoted Lukashenko as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to search for paths of mutual understanding
with the European Union and the United States," Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
He also lashed out at the Russian leadership for blocking the
integration processes and neglecting agreements within the
framework of the Belarus-Russia Union.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko warned that if Russia takes no concrete, real steps
toward integration with Belarus, he would reconsider his country's
foreign policy doctrine by giving priority to cooperation with the
West.
</P>
<P>
Observers in Minsk noted that it was the first time in the last
few years that Lukashenko had publicly avoided bellicose rhetoric
toward the West and U.S., Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
