<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Confident on Peace in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
said here Friday that he remains confident that a peace agreement
will be signed to end the war in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) and the Great Lakes region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba told visiting Botswanan President Festus Mogae that a
ceasefire agreement to put an end to the 11-month war in the third
largest African country will be signed as soon as the ministers of
defense and foreign affairs of the countries concerned adopt the
draft ceasefire agreement, which was approved last Sunday at the
officials meeting held here in the Zambian capital.
</P>
<P>
Everything is being done to ensure peace in DRC, said Chiluba,
who has been mandated by the Southern African Development
Community to mediate a peaceful solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
A regional summit scheduled for last Saturday has been delayed
because the draft agreement has not been adopted by the ministers.
</P>
<P>
All the warring parties involved in the conflict will sign the
agreement at the summit after it is adopted by the ministers.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also told Mogae it is regrettable that peace is still
elusive in Angola and fighting has raged again in the southern
African country despite the peace accord signed here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president expressed his hope that an end will be
put to the war as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He described the relations between Zambia and Botswana as
"extremely warm", saying the two countries have been cooperating
in various fields like agriculture, tourism, transportation and
that new cooperation will focus on combating cross-border crimes
such as drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Mogae praised Chiluba for his peace efforts in the DRC crisis,
and said Botswana supports his peace initiative.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the conflict in DRC will be resolved
 peacefully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
