<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Wants Good Relations With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou said Friday that Greece wanted calm and good relations
with neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
After briefing the Greek cabinet on his meeting in New York
with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem, Papandreou said that the
New York meeting was "a first step" toward this direction, but
adding that Greece should be cautious in its efforts to improve
bilateral relations with its eastern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas stressed that Greece hoped good relations with Turkey, but
would not have political dialogue with Turkey on Greece's
sovereign rights.
</P>
<P>
Greece was making efforts to have good communication with
Turkey in sectors of common interest, but the Greek government
would under no circumstances enter into political dialogue with
Turkey on Greece's sovereign rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Papandreou had talks with Cem on the sidelines of
a U.N-sponsored meeting on Kosovo. Both sides agreed to hold talks
at the level of Foreign Ministry senior officials on issues
relating to the economy, trade, environment, tourism, as well as
combating organized crime, illegal immigration, drugs and other
law and order issues.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting between the two ministers will take place in
September this year.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at odds over
decades for their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits, the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea and the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
