<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kouchner Named to Head U.N. Civilian Mission in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Friday decided to appoint Bernard Kouchner, a high-ranking
French Government official, as the head of the U.N. civil
operation in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, a U.N. spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came in a statement, issued by the U.N.
spokesman, saying that "the Secretary-General has informed the
President of the Security Council of his intention to appoint Mr.
Bernard Kouchner as his Special Representative to head the United
Nations Mission in Kosovo, Federal Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan appointed Jack Covey, who is an American, as
Principal Deputy to his Special Representative, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The four major components of the mission will each be headed by
a Deputy Special Representative as follows: Interim Civil
Administration -- Dominique Vian from France, Humanitarian
Affairs, Dennis McNamara from New Zealand -- Institution Building
-- Daan Everts from Netherlands, and Reconstruction -- Jolly Dixon
from the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the U.N. headquarters on Friday morning,
Annan told reporters that "It is, obviously, a very important
assignment -- this awesome responsibility in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"He (the Special Representative) will have to administer a
whole territory, make sure that the multi-ethnic society is able
to live side-by-side, and train about 3,000 police," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So it's quite a wide range of responsibilities, but what is
going on in the region makes it a crucial appointment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo, or UNMIK, is
currently headed by Sergio Vieira de Mello, who is the U.N.
under-secretary-general for humanitarian affairs, on interim
basis.
</P>
<P>
The civilian presence in Kosovo, set up under the June 10
Security Council resolution, is intended to undertake post-war
reconstruction in the Serbian province and provide an interim
administration under which the people of Kosovo are able to enjoy
substantial autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The daunting task, enormous in scope and complex in execution,
will surely last years before its completion. However, the United
Nations is facing with immediate challenges in Kosovo as the U.N.
mission lacks necessary police force to keep law and order and
funds to run the war-torn province, where revenge killings broke
out following massive returns of Albanian refugees from
neighboring countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
