<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Committee Supports Renewal of China's NTR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Ways and Means Committee in a vote on Thursday
voiced support to President Bill Clinton's decision to extend
China's Normal Trade Relations (NTR) and called on lawmakers to
kill a resolution aimed at severing business ties with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The committee decided by voice vote to back Clinton's decision
to renew China's NTR status, formally known as MFN (Most Favored
Nation), for another year.
</P>
<P>
The powerful committee also conducted a short debate on a
resolution calling for a rejection to Clinton's decision, and
decided to present it to the full house with a recommendation that
legislators to vote against it and continue business cooperation
with China.
</P>
<P>
"We must not turn our back on the prospect of economic progress
in China...It is not only in the U.S. commercial interest, but in
our strategic interest, to renew Normal Trade Relations with
China," said Representative Philip Crane, a Republican from the
State of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, some Congressmen told Chinese Ambassador
Li Zhaoxing on the Capitol Hill that they would "continuously and
unconditionally" support the extension of China's NTR status and
its entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton's decision to renew normal trade status with
China, made public on June 3, has won widespread support from both
business and political arenas. On June 14, Senate Majority leader
Trent Lott lent his backup for Clinton's decision, stressing that
even if the house veto it, it is unlikely for the Senate to take
up the issue.
</P>
<P>
During the past 20 years, the Congress has debated annually on
the NTR (MFN) status to China, but never succeeded in defeating
the presidential decision to extend the trade status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Ranks Third Language in Quebec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Spanish is becoming the third most
popular language in Canada's western province of Quebec, after
French and English.
</P>
<P>
Friday's "The Gazette" newspaper said that Spanish would have
surpassed Italian as Quebec's third most widely understood
language in 2001 if current trends continue.
</P>
<P>
The province has opened the door to beef-up instruction of
Spanish in schools, while universities are already struggling to
meet demand for Spanish courses, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
More than 190,000 Quebecers were able to hold a conversation in
either Italian or Spanish in 1996, with speakers of Italian
outnumbering those able to converse in Spanish by about 1,600, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
But because knowledge of Spanish spread almost 30 times faster
than that of Italian among Quebecers in the past decade, "we can
foresee that this language will have easily overtaken Italian by
the 2001 census," the report quoted a local demographer as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
