<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Fails to Propose End to Libya Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Friday presented a report to the Security Council, and did
not propose an official end to the sanctions against Libya due to
the delayed trial of Lockerbie suspects by a Scottish court
sitting in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Scottish Court on June 7 granted a request by defense
lawyers of the two Libyan suspects to delay the trial for six
months, Annan said, citing a court statement that "trial is
scheduled to start on or before February 4, 2000."
</P>
<P>
The two libyan suspects, who arrived in the Netherlands for the
trial before the Scottish court, was accused of their role in the
December 1988 bombing of an American airliner over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killing a total of 270 people.
</P>
<P>
"For that reason, I am not in a position to provide any factual
information on compliance by the Libya Arab Jamahiriya with the
relevant requirements," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. chief said, "I would like to point out that
the Libyan authorities have, indeed, provided assurances that they
will cooperate with the Scottish court."
</P>
<P>
Annan reported to the Security Council on April 5, saying that
the two Libyans had made their safe arrival in the Netherlands,
ready to be tried before the Scottish court.
</P>
<P>
In turn, the Security Council, in the April 8 presidential
statement, announced the suspension of the sanctions against Libya
because Tripoli has met the requirement to surrender the two
suspects for trial in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant Security Council resolution, the United Nations
is expected to announce the lifting of the sanctions against
Libya, imposed in 1992 and tightened in 1993, 90 days after Annan
reported the Libyan compliance.
</P>
<P>
Annan hosted a tripartite meeting on June 11 between the
Libyan, British and the U.S. permanent representatives to the
United Nations in order to assist the participants in clarifying
the positions of their governments regarding the requirements of
the Security Council resolutions for the lifting of sanctions
against Libya.
</P>
<P>
"The participants exchanged views and ideas and agreed that
there was need for a follow-up meeting," he said. "I hope that
further contacts will help to develop a constructive dialogue
between the parties concerned and will parties concerned and will
eventually lead to the normalization of relations among them."
</P>
<P>
"I also expressed the hope that the spirit of cooperation now
established will be maintained and that the start of the trial
will mark the beginning of a process leading to the normalization
of relations among all parties concerned for the benefit of the
international community as a whole," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
