<HEADLINE> Supervisors See Progress on Y2K Readiness in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- World leading supervisors have
agreed that significant progress on Year 2000 readiness and
contingency planning is being made in banking, securities and
insurance industries.
</P>
<P>
"The productive exchanges today between senior representatives
of major public and private financial sector organizations made
clear the significant progress on readiness being made in
financial markets," said Roger W Ferguson Jr, Chairman of the
Joint Year 2000 Council at the end of a round-table meeting
Thursday in the Swiss northern city of Basel on the Y2K effect on
world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"However, the meeting also indicated that much work is still to
be accomplished," Ferguson said. "Therefore we will need to remain
focused in our efforts and avoid complacency."
</P>
<P>
In its press release, the joint council pointed out that it is
especially critical over the coming months to convey the message
that meaningful progress is being made to the general public and
to maintain public confidence.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting organized by the Joint Year 2000 Council,
the participants reviewed progress made in achieving readiness of
the core components of the wrold's financial market infrastructure
and discussed risk mitigation strategies and contingency planning
necessary to minimize uncertainties and disturbances in financial
markets during the transition to 2000.
</P>
<P>
The joint council was founded in April 1998 by the Basel
Committee on Banking Supervision, the Committee on Payment and
Settlement Systems, the International Association of Insurance
Supervisors and the International Organization of Securities
Commissions. 
</P>
