<HEADLINE> Nine Sentenced to Death by Rwanda Criminal Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The sentences were handed down Wednesday in two separate joint
trials of 49 suspects who were charged with mass-murder of Tutsis
in Gisovu and Bwakira communes.
</P>
<P>
One person who pleaded guilty to killing one woman was handed
down a 15- year jail term, while 14 others were sentenced to jail
terms ranging from five to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Nine other people whose case files lacked evidence were
acquitted and they immediately walked home.
</P>
<P>
In another development, 47 genocide suspects in southwestern
Gikongoro prison were released Wednesday after the local criminal
court lacked enough evidence for charges brought against them.
</P>
<P>
Those set free were part of a group of 264 suspects whose files
were incomplete or empty and whose names had been submitted to
their home communes in search of evidence for their alleged
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan prisons are crammed with over 120,000 genocide suspects
accused of the 1994 massacres of Tutsis and opposition Hutus which
claimed the lives of more than 500,000 people. 
