<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Ireland launched a plan
on Friday to rescue the Northern Ireland peace process, after a
week of intensive talks failed to break the deadlock over
decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
The two governments said on Friday they hoped to set up a
power-sharing cabinet in Northern Ireland on July 15 and to get
Irish Republican Army disarmament started "within days".
</P>
<P>
They set out the moves in a formula to end a deadlock that has
stalled the year-old Good Friday agreement, according to a Reuters
report.
</P>
<P>
"All the parties have agreed to consult on these proposals,"
British Prime Minister Tony Blair was quoted as saying at the end
of five days of talks in Belfast. A joint statement said the
governments felt that both Protestant and Catholic leaders "will
support it accordingly."
</P>
<P>
The plan envisages ministers being nominated on July 15 with a
range of limited home rule powers actually transferred from London
to Belfast by July 18.
</P>
<P>
Blair said disarmament, which has been the biggest block on the
road to peace, could begin "within days."
</P>
<P>
The joint statement said the disarmament commission headed by
Canadian General John De Chastelain "will confirm a start to the
process of decommissioning."
</P>
<P>
However, it remains unknown how the plan will be received by
the rivaling parties in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
