<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Urges for Dialog to Solve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa said here Friday that dialog is the only way of solving
internal conflicts in some war-torn African countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a state banquet in honor of the visiting Mozambican
 President Joaquim Chissano, Mkapa said Tanzania does not hope to
see the bloody conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The blood which was shed in a number of African countries
during the struggle for national independence brought honor to
Africa, he said. However, the blood shed now in Africa is only a
shame to the continent.
</P>
<P>
"Why must we enter the 21st century with the shame?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa expressed hope that a peaceful solution will be found to
the present crisis facing the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
He paid special tribute to Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
for his tireless efforts and great patience in efforts to achieve
peace in DRC.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian President expressed hope that the recent
ministerial peace overtures in Lusaka, Zambia could bear fruits.
He urged the Congolese people not to let this good opportunity
toward achieving peace in their country pass, and appealed to them
to put an end to unnecessary loss of lives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mkapa called on donors, financiers and investors to
help develop the Mtwara Development Corridor, a key regional trade
link.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa invited them to attend a special conference on the
corridor to be held later this year in Dar es Salaam. He noted
that the multi-billion- dollar project is of vital importance to
the economic development of the African countries.
</P>
<P>
The corridor, running across Tanzania's southern regions, will
be a shortcut for the transportation of goods from the Indian
Ocean to Malawi and Zambia. The project is also expected to spur
the economic development of the forgotten areas in northern
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The four countries involved have held several meetings this
year to explore ways of developing the corridor, which will link
up the deep-water Mtwara Port in southwest Tanzania with the
Mbamba Bay on Lake Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Chissano, who arrived here Friday for a three-day visit to
Tanzania, will officially open the 23rd Dar es Salaam
International Trade Fair Saturday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
