<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls for Further Action on Population, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The current special session
of the U.N. General Assembly urged governments to attach more
importance to tackling the issue of population and development,
according to a draft document received Friday.
</P>
<P>
The draft, already adopted by the Ad Hoc Committee of the Whole,
called on governments to better understand the relationships among
population, poverty, gender inequity, health, education, the
environment and financial and human resources.
</P>
<P>
Governments also are urged to implement legislative and
administrative measures to promote public awareness on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The draft, scheduled to be adopted by delegates from over 170
counties at a night session Friday, said the implementation of the
Cairo recommendations has shown positive results.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have taken steps to integrate population
concerns into their development strategies, with mortality in most
countries continuing to fall in the five years since the adoption
of the Program of Action.
</P>
<P>
"The rising use of family planning methods indicates that there
is greater accessibility to family planning and that more and more
couples and individuals are able to choose the number and spacing
of their children," it said.
</P>
<P>
Among others, the final document would call for:
</P>
<P>
-- universal access to primary education by 2015 and
eliminating the gender gap in primary and secondary education by
2005,
</P>
<P>
-- reducing illiteracy of women and men, at least halving it
for women and girls by 2005 from the 1990 level,
</P>
<P>
-- establishing mechanisms to accelerate women's equal
participation and equitable representation at all levels of the
political process and public life,
</P>
<P>
-- developing and using indicators measuring access to and
choice of family planning and contraceptive methods,
</P>
<P>
-- reducing maternal mortality,
</P>
<P>
-- increasing young people's access to information and
education to reduce vulnerability to HIV infection,
</P>
<P>
-- increasing donor funding from 5.7 billion U.S. dollars in
2000 to 7.2 billion dollars in 2015, the deadline of the Cairo
Program of Action.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries are also urged to fulfil the agreed target of
0.7% of gross national product for overall official development
assistance.
</P>
<P>
The 3-day special session ends Friday which has reviewed and
appraised the implementation of the Program of Action of the 1994
Cairo Conference at the time the world population is reaching 6
billion as a result of an annual growth of 78 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Proposes Not to Give Official Status to German Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Italy tried to throw water Friday on
Germany's heated threats to boycott upcoming European ministers
meetings if German wasn't included as an official EU language.
</P>
<P>
Italian foreign ministry said Friday that the 11 languages of
the EU are on an equal level, but the use of French and English at
informal minister meetings "responds to the practical exigencies
to facilitate the exchange of the most direct exchange of views
possible among participants, keeping the need for interpretation
to a minimum."
</P>
<P>
The ministry added that maintaining the functioning of this
system requires that the EU avoid giving official status to such
languages as German, Spanish or Italian.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency ANSA, German government
sources Thursday confirmed a newspaper report that Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder sent a letter to the Finnish prime minister
saying Bonn would skip a series of informal meetings among
European leaders if his country's native tongue was no longer used
during EU negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The "Frankfurter Allgemaeine Zeitung" newspaper had reported
that Bonn was threatening the boycott after learning that German
was set to lose its official status once its six-month term at the
head of the EU expired.  
</P>
</TEXT>
