<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Rise 1.1 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department said
Friday that orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods
rebounded in May, rising 1.1 percent led by a big increase in
demand for aircraft, autos and other transportation products.
</P>
<P>
The Department said orders for transportation products rose 9.5
percent in May after having dropped by 12.5 percent the month
before.
</P>
<P>
In April, orders for all manufactured goods had fallen 1.4
percent, more than the government had initially estimated,
reflecting the big drop in demand for aircraft and other
transportation products.
</P>
<P>
Today's report showed that orders for durable goods also
bounced back in May, rising 1.2 percent which is slightly less
than a previous government estimate. Orders for such goods fell
2.4 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
But economists said the manufacturing sector is still not out
of difficulties because the strong dollar makes USA-made goods
more expensive for foreign buyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
