<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Moves To New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average moved up to a new record Friday as investors got
optimistic on the U.S. economy after a strong employment report.
</P>
<P>
The blue chip index closed up 72.82 at 11,139.24, surpassing
the record closing high of 11,107.19 set May 13. The Dow rose
586.68 points or 5.55 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 10.26 at 1,391.22 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq index rose 34.84 at 2,741.02, both moving into record
territories.
</P>
<P>
The stock market rallied as investors welcomed the strong
economic performance while discounting the fact that it could
translate into inflation after the Labor Department released an
employment report. According to the report, a total of 268,000
new jobs were created in June and average hourly earnings, a
key gauge of inflation pressures, increased by 3.7 percent in
the same month compared to a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Two days ago, the Federal Reserve decided to raise interest
rates by a quarter percentage point to cool off the economy and
prevent inflation from accelerating and dropped its "bias"
toward raising rates later. The action relieved investors' fears
about more rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 3.79 at 655.12 and the
American Stock Exchange index rose 7.47 at 802.42. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.09 at 456.51.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-8 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,695 up, 1,220 down and
623 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 583.74 million shares from 828.55
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
