<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Strict Food Import Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday ordered that inspectors at American ports prevent all
unsafe food products from entering the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in his weekly radio address that it is important
to make sure that food rejected at one U.S. port is not slipped
past inspectors at another.
</P>
<P>
He said he is also ordering the Customs Service and the Food
and Drug Agency to "rigorously enforce and expand our policy of
destroying imported food that poses a serious health threat rather
than risk letting it reach our grocery stores or the global market.
"
</P>
<P>
He said there is no evidence imported fruits and vegetables are
less safe than those grown here in the United States, "but some
recent outbreaks of food-borne illness have been traced in
imported foods."
</P>
<P>
A recent report said some importers are allowing contaminated
foods into the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on Congress to take further measures by granting
the Agriculture Department authority to impose civil penalties and
order mandatory recalls of unsafe meat and poultry.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Congress to cooperate with him on a program to
increase the number of inspectors and checks of high-risk food
products in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Forms Committee to Tackle UAE-Iranian Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) foreign ministers decided on Saturday to form an ad hoc
committee to tackle the territorial dispute between the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which comprises Oman, Qatar and Saudi Arabia,
will devise a mechanism to discuss the UAE-Iranian dispute over
three Gulf Islands, said the final communique issued after a brief
meeting of the GCC ministerial council held in the Saudi Red Sea
port city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi claims sovereignty over the strategic islands of Abu
Moussa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs, which are controlled by Tehran.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming Iran's readiness for direct talks with the UAE,
the GCC foreign ministers reaffirmed full solidarity with the
UAE's sovereignty over the islands and refused the Iranian
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Iran took control of the two Tunbs island in 1971 when British
colonialist forces pulled out of the region. It shared sovereignty
of Abu Moussa with the emirates until 1994 when it seized full
control of the island.
</P>
<P>
The UAE recently expressed dismay over the warming up of ties
between some GCC states, especially the Gulf heavyweight Saudi
Arabia, and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi fears that a cross-Gulf rapprochement will
relinquish GCC's support to the UAE in the territorial dispute.
</P>
<P>
Differences over the GCC-Iranian rapprochement and its possible
impact on the UAE-Iranian dispute led to a suspension of the GCC
ministerial session held in the Saudi capital of Riyadh on June 12.
</P>
<P>
A Qatari mediation later helped bridge the rift between the
UAE and Saudi Arabia, which agreed on the resumption of the
foreign ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
Qatar's Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani traveled to
both Riyadh and Abu Dhabi on June 19 in a bid to narrow the
differences between the two GCC countries.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
