<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gets FDI Offers of 5.96 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has received foreign
direct investment (FDI) offers of 288.8 billion taka (5.96 billion
U.S. dollars) since the present government was formed in June
1997, the national news agency BSS reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh received the offers in both joint-ventures and 100
percent foreign investment projects between June 23, 1996 and May
1999, sources of the Board of Investment (BOI) said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 425 projects had been registered with the BOI during
the last three years with opportunities for employment of over
94,000 people, they said.
</P>
<P>
The projects include five in the power sector involving 34.6
billion taka (713.4 million dollars), three in the telecom sector
with 38.25 billion taka (788.7 million dollars), two in the oil
and gas sector involving 23.65 billion taka (487.6 million
dollars) and 12 in cement manufacturing involving 11.45 billion
taka (236.1 million dollars), they noted.
</P>
<P>
About the pace of implementation, a BOI-conducted survey on 278
projects found that 63 were in production, 19 were in the
pipelines and the remaining were awaiting implementation.
</P>
<P>
Efforts were underway to further strengthen correlation and
coordination between the BOI and nine other agencies to speed up
implementation of the projects, said BOI Executive Chairman
Sirajuddin Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
The BOI was planning to make its periodic monitoring on
implementation of projects more affective, he said, adding that
the government was actively considering establishing industrial
parks in the capital city of Dhaka and on the other side of the
Jamuna River exclusively for the foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
