<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Denies Infringing on Ethiopian Embassy's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Eritrea government Saturday
denied having infringing on the right of the Ethiopian embassy in
Eritrea by seizing its property.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Eritrea has never, in any way hampered the
Ethiopian embassy or infringed on any of its inherent rights,"
said the Eritrean Foreign Ministry in a press statement reaching
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The denial was made after the Ethiopian government claimed in
a press statement dated July 1, 1999 which charged that the
Eritrean government had seized Ethiopian embassy property by
"confiscating documents sent in a pouch by the Ethiopian Ministry
of Foreign Affairs to the Embassy."
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, it was Ethiopia which expelled all Eritrean
diplomatic and technical staff in 1998 and denied the Eritrean
ambassador and his deputy freedom of movement, said the Eritrean
statement.
</P>
<P>
It added that Ethiopia also "declared Eritrea's Permanent
Representative to the Organization of African Unity (OAU) persona
non grata and ordered him to leave the country within 24 hours"
and on February 11, 1999 "armed agents of the government of
Ethiopia entered forcibly the residence of the (Eritrean)
ambassador."
</P>
<P>
"Addis Ababa is issuing these claims to further 'muddy the
waters'. No one should be midled," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that the Ethiopian claims happened just one week
away from the summit of the Organization of African Unity in
Algiers, at which Eritrea's legitimate grievances regarding
Ethiopia's violations would be discussed.
</P>
<P>
"Ethiopia's violations must receive the unfettered and direct
attention they merit," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
