<HEADLINE> Pakistan Calls for Third-Party Involvement in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan said Saturday that
third-party involvement is essential to resolve the current crisis
in the disputed Kashmir region as India has shut all doors to
bilateral dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"They have shut doors on all kinds of dialogue. When bilateral
course is sterile, then third-party involvement will be useful,"
Foreign Office spokesman Tariq Altaf told a regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said India's obdurate refusal to hold bilateral talks has
proved that third-party involvement, "be in the form of
arbitration, mediation or any other role, is not only desirable
but essential."
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about the possibility of a meeting
between Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and U.S. President Bill
Clinton, Altaf said: "I am confident President Clinton has a
particular role to play (in this situation), if a meeting takes
place (between Sharif and Clinton), it will be extremely
productive." 
</P>
