<HEADLINE> Canada Releases U.S. Fishing Boat With Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Fisheries Department
has announced the release of an American fisherman and his boat
held for 24 hours on suspicion of illegal fishing in disputed
waters.
</P>
<P>
The Lesley Anne, skippered by Dale Bosworth of Petersburg,
Alaska, was freed Friday afternoon with a warning, the department
said in an announcement released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bosworth, who was alone, was spotted fishing for black cod in
north Pacific waters claimed by both Canada and the United States
when he was detained on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Robert Martinolich, a Canadian Fisheries Department official,
told reporters that "based on the circumstances, the most
appropriate action" was to let the American fisherman "leave the
Canadian zone with a warning."
</P>
<P>
The seizure has sparked a strong reaction from Alaskan Governor
Tony Knowles, who expressed "collective outrage" in a letter to U.
S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
He said the seizure was "beyond the norms of international law"
and required "reparations and a formal apology by the Canadian
government."
</P>
<P>
Knowles's spokesman Bob King threatened to undo the good
relations rebuilt after a salmon treaty was signed just on
Wednesday in Washington, as a result of five years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"It's an unfortunate time" because the U.S. Senate is still
considering the financial terms of the treaty, "and we hope there
are no repercussions," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
