<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Flood Crest Passes Jingjiang Section of Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- This year's first flood peak on the
Yangtze River is passing through the river's Jingjiang section.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yangtze River Water Resources Committee, the
crest passed the city of Yichang near the Three Gorges Project in
Hubei Province on Thursday, where water levels were approaching
the danger mark of 52 meters with a maximum flow rate of 47,400
cubic meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Flood waters from the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze
gained force and rose above the danger level at Shishou in Hubei
and formed this year's first crest on the Yangtze. From there
downstream to the city of Jiujiang in Jiangxi Province, the flood
water will continue for the next few days, according to Professor
Ge Shouxi of the Committee's Hydrology Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The committee predicted that the flood crest will reach Jianli
in Hubei on July 6 and arrive in Wuhan, capital of Hubei, the
following day.
</P>
<P>
Water levels will be 27.2 meters in Wuhan when the flood peak
arrives and will drop to 20.52 meters at Jiujiang and further to
about 14.75 meters at Datong in Anhui Province by July 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Polar Expedition To Study Effects Of Temperatures On Global Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are various opinions about the impact of the rising
temperatures, but they haven't been confirmed, said Chen Liqi, the
expedition's chief scientist, who noted that the rising
temperatures are getting a great deal of attention.
</P>
<P>
Data indicates that average temperatures around the world have
gone up one or two degrees centigrade over the past 150 years and
that the phenomenon is quite clear in the polar extremes. Some
people say that the rising temperatures will cause the tundra to
shrink, resulting in a softening of the ground, which is bad for
building, while some others believe it will help fishing and the
expansion of forests in polar regions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese expedition will try to find a proper answer to
these questions, said Chen, who believed that rising temperatures
have something to do with last year's flooding on the Yangtze
river and the drought in some parts of China.
</P>
<P>
The Snow Dragon is a very modern icebreaker that carries 124
scientists and journalists. It left Shanghai on July 1 and is
traveling at 15 nautical miles per hour and is expected to pass
the Korean Strait at 8:00 this evening.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will mainly study the effects of the North Pole
on the global climate, especially on China, the ecological system
in Arctic waters, and the atmosphere, geology, fishing, and marine
environment of the area.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Shaohong, the captain of the ship, says that it was
originally scheduled for a 60-day journey but that will be
extended about 8 days because of some course adjustments in its
trip through the Sea of Japan, the Bering Sea, and into the Canada
Basin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
