<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Suffering From Heatwave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Temperatures above 36 degrees
centigrade have hit Beijing for the past nine days, the longest
hot spell since 1942, according to Wang Guitian, of the Beijing
Meteorology Station.
</P>
<P>
He says that northern China had only 26.4 millimeters of
precipitation for June, 47.6 millimeters below average, and the
low humidity and clear skies combined with a warm high pressure
front over much of East Asia has produced the continued hot days.
</P>
<P>
However, the hot weather has benefited cold drink producers.
One factory director said that daily sales of cold drinks and ice-
cream have increased more than 50 percent. Average daily sales of
air conditioners in these days were four times that at the
beginning of June and some stores have even run out of stock.
</P>
<P>
But, Wang says, the hot weather is not affecting work or daily
life in a big way because many people now work either in offices
or at home with air conditioners and labor intensity is down
because of technological development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
