<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak FM Returns With Support of Islamic Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz Saturday expressed his full satisfaction over support of the
Islamic Countries Foreign Ministers (ICFM) to Pakistan's stance on
the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remark when talking to reporters on his return
from the 26th session of the ICFM in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso,
which brought together foreign ministers from the member countries
of the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
The Pak foreign minister noted that the ICFM unanimously
adopted two resolutions to express solidarity with Islamabad in
the current border confrontation with India.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time that foreign ministers of over 50
Islamic countries have adopted two separate resolutions on
Kashmir, one reaffirming its traditional stand on the core issue
of Jammu and Kashmir and the other on the current tension along
the Line of Control (LoC)," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Describing it as a major success for Pakistan "at a critical
time", Aziz said that Islamic countries fully endorsed Pakistan's
stand on Kashmir and gave their "loud and unequivocal" support for
Pakistan's security, territorial integrity and political
independence.
</P>
<P>
The Pak foreign minister said the resolution on the Kashmir
issue reaffirmed the Kashmiris' right to self-determination,
condemned the human rights abuses in the India-held valley and
called for settlement of the issue under the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The second resolution expressed deep concern over the serious
escalation of tension caused by heavy Indian shelling and air
strikes across the LoC, said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Lauding Pakistan's peace initiatives for defusing tension, the
resolution further urged the two sides to exercise restraint and
resume dialogue as agreed in the Lahore Declaration, he added.
</P>
<P>
Aziz disclosed that the ICFM agreed to appoint a special
representative on Kashmir, whom he hoped that the OIC secretary
general will shortly appoint even if India refuses to accept.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day stay in Ouagadougou, Aziz held bilateral
meetings with foreign ministers of 17 countries. During these
meetings, he explained to his counterparts the detailed background
of the current tension in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
On his way back, Aziz made a short stay in Paris Friday where
he met his French counterpart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
