<HEADLINE> Pak FM Renews Invitation to Indian FM to Visit Islamabad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj
Aziz Saturday renewed his invitation to his Indian counterpart
Jaswant Singh to visit Pakistan to reduce tension on the Line of
Control (LoC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"My invitation to Jaswant Singh still stands," the foreign
minister said while talking to reporters here on his arrival after
attending the 26th Islamic Countries Foreign Ministers' Conference
in Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
Aziz first extended the invitation to Singh when he visited New
Delhi on June 12 in a bid to carry forward the bilateral dialogue
process to defuse the tension on the LoC. However, India has not
yet responded to the offer.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, Aziz said, has been pleading for a negotiated
settlement of the crisis in Kargil and also the Kashmir dispute as
a whole and that is why he went to New Delhi last month.
</P>
<P>
"Our proposal to India is clear. Let's sit down and talk," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Dispelling the impression that Pakistan has violated the LoC,
he said Pakistan respects the LoC but questioned as to where is
the LoC.
</P>
<P>
He said the LoC existed only in map, adding there is a need for
its verification by the U.N. observers. "We hope we will find a
mechanism for respect to the LoC," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the possibility of a full-fledged war, the foreign
minister said, "Danger of war has reduced." However, he said
Pakistan will defend itself if war is imposed on it. 
</P>
