<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Submits Three More Nominees to Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's president Olusegun Obasanjo
Friday sent three new ministerial nominees to the Senate for
screening, reported The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The nominees include Ime Okubudo, Mohammed Shatta, Hajiya
Aishatu Ismail,
</P>
<P>
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Okubudo's nomination is believed to replace Udoma, whose name
though had been confirmed by the senate, failed to show up on the
June 30 cabinet inauguration.
</P>
<P>
Although no reason has been given for his action, he allegedly
rejected the appointment because he was offered the post of a
junior minister.
</P>
<P>
The president, in a letter addressed to the senate president
Chief Evan Enwerem, apologized to the senators for his failure to
officially invite them to the swearing in of the ministers and
said the oversight was not deliberate.
</P>
<P>
The Senate, or the upper house of Nigeria's Legislature
confirmed 42 out of the President's 49 ministerial nominees on
June 23 after a marathon debate, and latter on June 29 okayed
another five of the president's seven nominees. 
</P>
