<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges Youths To Emulate Nkomo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe Friday
challenged Zimbabwean youths to emulate late Vice-President Joshua
Nkomo whom he described as a principled and committed leader who
sacrificed a lot for the liberation of the country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told thousands of mourners who gathered to view Nkomo's
body at Ascot race course in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest
city that the late Vice-president spent nearly 50 years fighting
for the liberation of the country and was never deterred by long
years of incarceration and as a refuge in other countries, the
Zimbabwe News agency Ziana reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"What we see in this great man is a leadership of commitment,
which is not tribal or regionalistic," he said, adding that Nkomo
was a true national leader and a man of the people who was above
tribal, religious and ethnic politics.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said Nkomo left a heritage of unity and that people
should view and identify themselves first and foremost as
Zimbabweans and not along their tribes.
</P>
<P>
He said Nkomo suffered a lot in prison and detention and it was
him who started the liberation struggle which brought about
independence and democracy to the country.
</P>
<P>
"It was not easy being in prison for so long where there was
poor food and torturing, but for the principled Nkomo he was
prepared to die there for the liberation of the country," Mugabe
said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the government should also be people
oriented, by taking into consideration the feelings, aspirations,
sufferings and needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
"If you feel we are not doing this, then you have a right to
complain. If we do not take care of the people's problems, then
you can say we are not walking in the footsteps of the great man,
Joshua Nkomo," he said, adding that Nkomo was a hero of heroes.
</P>
<P>
Nkomo died Thursday in Harare. His body was taken to his
Matsheumhlophe residence in Bulawayo Friday for viewing by members
of the public. The body will be flown back to Harare on Sunday,
where it will lie in State before burial on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
