<HEADLINE> Australian Serbs Protest at Expulsion of Serbs From Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred Australian Serbs
protested Saturday in Australia's biggest city of Sydney against
the expulsion of thousands of Serbs from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators gathered at Town Hall in central Sydney,
carrying signs and banners saying "Stop the Exodus" and "Keep the
U.N. Promise."
</P>
<P>
About 200 Australian police also gathered at Town Hall and
other places throughout the city where the protesters were
expected to march.
</P>
<P>
Ilija Glisic, president of the Serbian National Federation of
Australia, said the protesters wanted Serbs in Kosovo to get more
protection than what was currently being given by NATO and the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He said 71,000 Serbs had been forced to leave Kosovo in the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of civilians had been killed and hundreds of homes
had been looted and destroyed since ethnic Albanians were allowed
to return to Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We want equal treatment to everyone in Kosovo, to make sure
everyone can go back to Kosovo, not just the Albanians," Glisic
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We want to ensure people's rights are protected, their
property is protected and the cultural and historical monuments in
Kosovo are protected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Protester Predrag Rancac said many Albanians were getting their
revenge on Serbs, torching houses and killing civilians as they
returned home.
</P>
<P>
"We are protesting at the behavior of NATO troops in Kosovo,"
he said.
"They are not following the peace agreement reached. They are
freely letting Albanians take revenge."
</P>
<P>
The demonstration ended peacefully earlier Saturday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
