<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Remains World's Leading Air Cargo Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals
Limited (HACTL) announced Saturday that its throughput for the
first five months of 1999 achieved a 7 percent year-on-year
increase and it is confident that Hong Kong remains the world's
leading air cargo hub.
</P>
<P>
HACTL, which owns 80 percent market share in Hong Kong,
predicts modest growth for the year, so long as Hong Kong sustains
its current market conditions, according to Anthony Wong, managing
director of HACTL.
</P>
<P>
"Our operations have steadily returned to the high levels of
reliability that our customers associated with us before the
transfer to Chek Lap Kok," said Wong. "Through innovative efforts
to enhance our services, our operational standards have now
surpassed those of Kai Tak."
</P>
<P>
"HACTL is committed to position SuperTerminal 1 as a one-stop
service integration center," said Wong, calling SuperTerminal 1 as
a world-class air cargo facility with full automated systems.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, our Express Center is dedicated to serving the
needs of the fast-growing express cargo business. Together, they
will ensure Hong Kong's position as the world's leading air cargo
hub," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Chek Lap Kok International Airport, a landmark
project that cost nearly 20 billion U.S. dollars together with its
related infrastructure facilities, went into operation on July 6,
1998. The 73-year-old Kai Tak Airport was closed at the same time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak to Receive French Mirage Planes as Scheduled: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will receive Mirage III
combat jets and Agosta-class submarines from France as per
schedule as there is no embargo on their delivery, Foreign
Minister Sartaj Aziz said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question during his press briefing on return from
Burkina Faso where he attended a meeting of the Organization of
Islamic Conference, Aziz said he discussed the issue with French
officials in Paris Friday and the officials said there is no
restriction on the delivery.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said he met his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine and Jean
David Levitte, diplomatic adviser to the French president, and
discussed with them a host of issues focusing on regional security
and the tension on the Line of Control (LoC) in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that France may delay the delivery of Mirage
combat jets to Pakistan as a result of the fighting along the LoC.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think that the delivery will be stopped and according
to the program one Agosta submarine is due to be delivered to
Pakistan on July 8," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said that France and Pakistan agreed that meaningful efforts
be made for de-escalation in Kargil of Kashmir and dialogue be
revived between Pakistan and India in the spirit of the Lahore
Declaration signed by the two countries to resolve the Kashmir
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also conveyed a letter from Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif to French President Chirac relating to the recent
escalation in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said he had constructive discussions with his French
counterpart on the dangerous escalation that had taken place in
the Kargil sector on the LoC.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed on the urgent need to reduce tension between
Pakistan and India, particularly as both countries have nuclear
capability," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and France also agreed that in dealing with the Kargil
situation both Pakistan and India should respect the LoC, said
Aziz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
