<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaitis Start Voting For New Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti voters flocked to
the 190 polling stations across the country Saturday morning to
elect their ninth National Assembly (parliament) since 1963.
</P>
<P>
The eighth National Assembly was constitutionally dissolved by
Emir Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah in March 1998, following a deadlock
in relations between the parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations in 42 schools across the state opened at 08:00
(0500 GMT) and will close at 20:00 (1700 GMT). Results are
expected to be made known at about midnight in the day.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, nearly 113,000 males are
eligible for the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
A total of 288 registered candidates are contesting 50
parliamentary seats at the 25 constituencies in what is likely to
be the country's last all-male elections.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 500 people had originally registered for the race, but
over 200 of them pulled out as the deadline for withdrawal came on
June 28.
</P>
<P>
Among the 288 candidates, roughly one third are new face.
</P>
<P>
Since there are no official political parties in Kuwait,
candidates are representing different government-tolerated
political groups. Some prominent and influential political figures
are even running as independents.
</P>
<P>
Tribal groups are expected to be dominant elements in the
elections as more than half of the constituencies are considered
to be tribal areas.
</P>
<P>
Candidates in the three main Islamic groups -- the Islamic
Popular Movement or Salaf, the Islamic Constitutional Movement
(ICM) and the Shia National Islamic Alliance (NIA) -- are also
believed to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
Like other oil rich Gulf nations, Kuwait suffered grave losses
over the past couple of years due to the sagging oil prices in the
global market, domestic issues, especially economy-related ones,
have been dominating the platforms of most candidates during the
past two months of fierce campaign.
</P>
<P>
The candidates called on the private sector to play a more
important role in the country's economy by employing more
national manpower, and promised to work on it if elected to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Some candidates also focused their speeches on the importance
of cooperation between the parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation crises triggered by policy differences between the
legislature and the executive authority have led to the
dissolution of the last parliament and the mass resignation of
the former cabinet in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Compared with economy, national security, the key issue in
the 1992 elections, took a backseat in the elections campaign
speeches of most candidates.
</P>
<P>
Most candidates and voters said that they are feeling "more
secure at home and the defense agreements Kuwait signed with
foreign countries after the 1991 Gulf war are the main reason for
less preoccupation with national security in 1999."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
