<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Closes Illegal Fuel Filling Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has closed
down 25 fuel filling stations in capital Nairobi as they have no
licenses or site plans.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary Crispus Mutitu of the Energy Ministry
Friday announced that among those closed stations, 22 did not have
licenses, 23 had on site plans while five were built on road
reserves and two had defective fire fighting equipment.
</P>
<P>
He said his government would continue to crack down on the
illegal depots until those guilty are kicked out of operation,
mass media reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the illegal stations comes in the wake of deaths
of two people who were burned to death in a fuel-related explosion
Wednesday evening at a makeshift filling station in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Mutitu warned that anybody found to have set up petroleum
retailing business illegally would be charged in courts of law and
be required to demolish the installation.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that liberalization of the petroleum sector
was not meant to usher in indiscipline and reckless disregard of
the law.
</P>
<P>
A committee of all licensing organization would be set up to
approve licenses for filling stations and to avoid ambiguity in
issuing such licences, Mutitu announced.
</P>
<P>
To streamline the operation of the sector in the country, other
measures to be undertaken include no allocation of road reserves
for fuel retailing, inspection sites and installation to ensure
compliance with safety and environmental requirements before
issuing licenses, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
