<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Expanding Industrial Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial sector continued
to grow in the first four months this year, according to figures
released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The added value of industry from January to April increased by
9.7 percent on an annual basis to reach 617 billion yuan (about 77
billion U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
The added value of light industry during the period stood at
261 billion yuan, up 9.4 percent year on year, and that of heavy
industry 356 billion yuan, up 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed an added value of 353.3 billion yuan from the
state owned and state holding enterprises, which accounted for
more than half of the gross industrial output in the four months.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, collectively-owned enterprises, a component of
the public assets, reported an added value of 104.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The added value of enterprises with overseas investment and
investment from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan regions amounted to
123.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The statistics covered all enterprises in the state and non-
state sectors with the annual product sales revenue at and above
five million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
