<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Fighters Rescue Flood-Threatened Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Zookeepers have called in fire
fighters to pump water out of China's second largest zoo in
Shanghai, which has been beseiged by floodwaters for the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
The zoo is in a low-lying area in the western part of the city
and the heaviest rainfall in the century almost turned it into a
marine world with a meter of water.
</P>
<P>
Zookeepers had to move a three-day-old giraffe to the second
floor of their office building as water levels rose as high as the
mother's neck in the animal shelter, located at the lowest point
in the zoo.
</P>
<P>
The zoo bought two truckloads of bricks to build a dam around
the giraffe shelter and called in four fire engines Friday to pump
the water out.
</P>
<P>
The chimps and gorillas moved a bit faster and found
comfortable refuges on top of rockeries or trees in the primate
building.
</P>
<P>
Even though the firefighters have been working hard to move
half the water out of the zoo, half of it is still under water and
the keepers are using boats to carry feed to the animals, and,
since the kitchen lost its electricity, their meals have been cut
from three to two every day.
</P>
<P>
However, the two brown bears seem glad to have a new swimming
pool down in the front yard, but it's too bad they can't be
watched - the zoo has been closed to visitors for the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
The zoo has successfully moved all 6,000 animals to dry ground
except for two pheasants, which drowned at the height of the
flooding. "This is the first time for anything like this to happen
in the zoo's 45-year history, said the curator Shi Xinquan.
</P>
<P>
He said that now that the rainfall has stopped, they will be
able to clean up and reopen the zoo on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Ready to Evacuate Residents Near Mayon Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Saturday that evacuation centers are ready to help residents
living in the areas near Mayon Volcano if the volcano's eruption
forces them to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview here Saturday morning, Defense Secretary
Orlando Mercado said that regional and provincial disaster
coordinating councils have put in place disaster relief and
prevention measures in the area as Mayon has showed signs of
imminent explosion.
</P>
<P>
"Our evacuation centers are ready. We have already alerted all
those concerned. Even our armed forces are ready to help," said
Mercado, who also chairs the National Disaster Coordinating
Council.
</P>
<P>
He said that his office has made needed preparations since
Mayon started spewing smoke and ash on June 22.
</P>
<P>
While the government is ready to assist residents there, the
biggest enemy remains the stubbornness of some residents who
insist on staying at their homes, Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Mayon, about 330 kilometers southeast of Manila, may erupt in
the coming days or weeks, and the country's disaster and relief
agencies should beef up contingency measures for an eruption,
experts warned.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology
(Phivolcs) said Friday that Mayon has showed signs of imminent
explosion and alert level two is being maintained.
</P>
<P>
Alert level two means the permanent danger zone around Mayon
has been extended from six kilometers to seven kilometers and
people within the danger zone should be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Prompted by the imminent explosion of the volcano, the Albay
provincial disaster coordinating center hastened the evacuation of
about 18,000 residents within the danger zone.
</P>
<P>
While the Education Department Friday ordered the suspension of
classes in schools in the vicinity of Mayon, Defense Secretary
Mercado ordered the pre-positioning in Albay of resources like
food supplies, transportation and manpower.
</P>
<P>
Mayon had a mild eruption on June 22 and the eruption only
lasted about 10 minutes. No casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
During the eruption, a high column of ash and smoke was seen on
Mayon's crater, but the volcano calmed down one hour after its
eruption.
</P>
<P>
Mayon, the most active volcano in the world, has erupted at
least 40 times since 1616. The volcano's eruption on February 2,
1993 killed 78 people and affected 17,119 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
