<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Passenger Traffic Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Total passenger traffic between January and March reached 3.67
billion ridership, 4.78 percent more than the figure for the same
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
The highway sector registered 3.37 billion ridership during the
period, a year-on-year rise of 5.4 percent. A total of 245 million
people traveled by trains in the three months, 1.2 percent more
than that in the same 1998 period, and 13 million people traveled
by air during the period, up 5.2 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
However, the waterway sector reported a year-on-year decline of
14.5 percent in ridership. Only 49 million people traveled by ship
during the period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, total freight traffic in the January-March period
reached 2.97 billion tons, dipping 0.8 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The highway sector suffered a 1.2 percent drop to 2.3 billion
tons, and the waterway sector handled 276 million tons of cargo,
down 2.1 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The railway and civil aviation sectors, however, saw an
increase in freight traffic during that time. The railway sector
carried 380 million tons of cargo, up 2.7 percent, and the freight
traffic in the civil aviation sector surged 19.3 percent to 361,
700 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
