<HEADLINE> China's Investment in Industry Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's investment in many
industrial sectors underwent a decline in the first four months
this year with investment in the communications sector keeping an
upward trend, according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures from the bureau showed that total investment in
industry between January and April dropped by 3.1 percent year-on-
year to 109.7 billion yuan (about 13.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, 57 billion yuan went to the energy sector,
down 7.2 percent from the same 1998 period, and a sum of 13.4
billion yuan was directed to machinery and electronics sector, a
dip of 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Transportation, Postal and Telecommunication services continued
to enjoy a considerable inflow of funds. Investment in the sector
during the period hit 71 billion yuan, surging 38 percent on an
annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Light industry and textile industry also saw an increase of
investment in the four months. Funds channeled to the sectors
amounted 13.5 billion yuan, edging up 1.4 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
