<HEADLINE> China's Production of Energy Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's production of energy
dropped in the January-April period this year, according to the
latest figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Total energy production in the first four months amounted to
321.6 million tons of standard coal equivalent, down by 3.3
percent from the figure for the same 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
Production of coal dropped by 3.7 percent to 306.2 million tons,
while that of crude oil edged up 0.9 percent to 52.7 million tons
and that of gasoline grew by 11.5 percent to 12.1 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, power output increased by 4.7 percent to 372
billion kwh. The output of thermal power output amounted to 327
billion kwh, up 8.9 percent on an annual basis, while that of
hydro-electric power output plummeted 20.2 percent to 41 billion
kwh.  
</P>
</TEXT>
