<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Govt Extends Amnesty to "Terrorists" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
decided to extend general amnesty for terrorists to surrender till
July 30 this year, newspapers here reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was voiced by Home Minister Mohammad Nasim on
Friday, when 386 armed terrorists officially surrendered to the
government in the southwestern Khulna district, laying down their
arms.
</P>
<P>
The outlaws, the second batch in a row within a month,
deposited 282 firearms, including one light machine gun, five
rifles and 45 Indian Shutter guns. Some 210 persons laid down
their arms in early June at the first surrender ceremony in
Jessore district, 146 kilometers southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
The combing operation to catch the outlaws and other gun-toting
elements started on April 22 and will continue after the deadline,
said the home minister. "A more stringent combing operation will
start immediately after the end of the deadline" and "the
operation will continue until the last bastion of terrorists is
squashed," he declared.
</P>
<P>
He urged terrorists still underground to return to normal life,
promising to do everything to rehabilitate them.
</P>
<P>
In the over-two-month countrywide operation, some 6,5000
suspects have been held by law-enforcing agencies, mainly in the
southwestern districts, in the wake of a spurt of violence.
</P>
<P>
The country's southwestern region has reportedly become a haven
for outlawed extremists, with fierce rivalry resulting in many
deaths and rising crimes. Many people there have deserted their
ancestral homes in search of security, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
