<HEADLINE> New Zealand FM Opposes Advocacy of Merging NZ into Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister of Foreign
Affairs and Trade Don Mckinnon has showed his opposition to the
advocacy of merging New Zealand into Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post Saturday quoted the minister as saying that
advocating New Zealand become "the seventh state" of Australia
would be "death" for any New Zealand political party.
</P>
<P>
Mckinnon made the remarks Friday in response to a question
raised at the University of Otago's 34th annual foreign policy
school in Dunedin, a city on New Zealand's South Island.
</P>
<P>
"If Australia becomes a republic, New Zealand will soon follow
suit," the Wellington-based newspaper quoted the minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Mckinnon said closer economic links are likely, given extensive
travel and other ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
If European Union countries with different languages could form
 close ties, it "would be the wrong thing" for two similar
countries in the South Pacific "to be heading in opposing
directions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gradually increased cooperation would be acceptable, Mckinnon
said, adding he is not sure that people would be prepared to
accept change over a few key issues, such as sovereignty or
separate currency, either this generation or next. 
</P>
</TEXT>
