<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK, U.N. Command Meeting Yields No Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Generals of the Democratic People
's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the U.S.-led United Nations
Command (UNC) remained wide apart after meeting for the third time
over the recent inter-Korean naval clash, press reports said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the 90-minute meeting in the U.N. truce village Panmunjom on
Friday, Lieutenant General of the DPRK People's Army Ri Chan Bok
said South Korean warships intruded into the DPRK's territorial
waters more than 70 times after the two sides exchanged gunfire in
the Yellow Sea on June 15.
</P>
<P>
He said that upholding the so-called Northern Limit Line -- a
sea border unilaterally demarcated by the UNC in 1953 -- is "in
defiance of the arms truce" and "in serious violation of
international law."
</P>
<P>
To prevent further clashes in the Yellow Sea, Ri said the U.S.-
led UNC should abandon the Northern Limit Line and withdraw all
warships in the disputed area. Any aggressive act and military
provocation against the DPRK's territorial waters should be
stopped while those responsible for the June 15 crossfire should
be punished.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides should first reach an agreement in
principle at the general level before sitting down on related
practical measures.
</P>
<P>
The UNC delegation, led by U.S. Major General Michael Dunn,
defended the Northern Limit Line as sea border. The meeting broke
up without any agreement like its predecessors on June 15 and 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0161 </DOCNO>
