<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Friday
approved the second annual loan totaling 40 million U.S. dollars
for Tajikistan under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (
ESAF) to support the government's 1999-2000 economic program.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan's three-year ESAF was approved in June 1998 in the
amount of 128 million dollars, and in December 1998 was augmented
to 134 million dollars, of which 54 million has been disbursed. (
IMF-Tajikistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Tea production in Kenya is negatively impacted by
the unfavorable weather conditions, which has resulted in tea
growth below normal seasonal levels in the week to June 28, Africa
's leading tea trader, Africa Tea Brokers (ATB) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ATB said temperatures were low in most of the main tea
growing areas while hails damaged tea in some areas of Rift Valley
Province in west Kenya. (Kenya-Weather-Tea)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Commerce Department said Friday that orders
to U.S. factories for manufactured goods rebounded in May, rising
1.1 percent led by a big increase in demand for aircraft, autos
and other transportation products.
</P>
<P>
The Department said orders for transportation products rose 9.5
percent in May after having dropped by 12.5 percent the month
before. (US-Factory Orders)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panama Canal will keep the present tolls
after its restoration to the Panamanian sovereignty in the year
2000, Alberto Aleman Zubieta, the interoceanic waterway
administrator, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Panamanian cabinet council has
approved the stability of tolls starting next January 1. (Panama-
Canal Tolls)
</P>
<P>
