<HEADLINE> Tuberculosis Cases Increases in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The increase of Tuberculosis (TB)
cases all over Myanmar is due to the spread of HIV/AIDS and TB
virus becoming immune to the drugs.
</P>
<P>
The remarks was made by Myanmar Minister of Health
Major-General Ket Sein at a TB control meeting here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ket Sein disclosed that there are about 100,000 TB patients in
Myanmar, saying that half of them are found with the mucus from
which the disease can spread to others.
</P>
<P>
The number of deaths caused by the disease is the second
highest in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, HIV has been found in 0.7 percent and 0.97 percent
of blood donors respectively in Yangon and Mandalay, two major
cities in the country, after they went through blood test in
hospitals where HIV test kits are provided.
</P>
<P>
According to available official figures, there were 17,846 HIV
cases and 2,337 AIDS cases in Myanmar by the end of 1997. The
figures for 1998 have not been published yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
