<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flow of Major Rivers Continues to Rise in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Most of the major rivers in three of
the Bangladesh's four river basins continued to rise Friday as
heavy monsoon rains pounded vast areas of the country during the
past several days, press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Excepting those in the southeastern hill basin, the major
rivers in the Ganges, Brahmaputra and Meghna basins registered
further rise, the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center (FFWC)
officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, excepting the Surma River at two points, all the
rivers were still flowing below their respective danger marks,
they added.
</P>
<P>
The flash floods, caused by onrush of hilly waters from
upstream region in India, inundated many low-lying areas of the
northeastern and northwestern districts of Sylhet, Sunamganj and
Kurigram during the past few days, local officials said, adding
that the situation still remained static on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Vast areas in Sylhet and Sunamganj districts and some low-lying
areas of Kurigram district were inundated due to torrential rains
and onrush of hilly waters.
</P>
<P>
The Brahmaputra River recorded rise, the Ganges continued to
rise at all points and most of the rivers in the Meghna basin
registered further rise while all the rivers of the southeastern
hill basin recorded fall during the last 24-hours ending 09-00
hours on Friday, a FFWC bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
Moderate to heavy rainfall at all points with very heavy fall
at one or two places over the Brahmaputra and the Ganges basins
were recorded during the period with the monsoon being active over
the country, the bulletin noted.
</P>
<P>
Besides, light to heavy fall at all places over the Meghna
basin and light to moderately heavy rainfall at all places over
the southeastern hill basin were registered during the same
period, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
