<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Forest Affected by Oil Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- About 700,000 hectares of natural
forest have disappeared in Ecuador since 1968 when the Texaco and
Cepe-Texaco oil firms started oil exploitation in the country.
</P>
<P>
This issue was a subject of discussions in Quito Thursday and
Friday during a series of lectures organized by the Environment,
Energy and Mines, and Finance ministries.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran Environment Vice Minister Jorge Alban said, "oil
exploitation has opened roads and unleashed processes of
colonization and of massive exploitation of timber."
</P>
<P>
The Ecuadoran Amazonia has the biggest natural forest in the
country and rich wildlife.
</P>
<P>
The zone is the home of eight ethnic groups who use more than
600 kinds of plants for medical purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
