<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Govt Slashes Crude Palm Oil Export Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
announced a cut in export taxes on crude palm oil (CPO) to 10
percent from 30 percent in line with falling international prices,
The Jakarta Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industry and Trade Rahardi Ramelan said the cut is
expected to give more incentives for local CPO producers to export
their products.
</P>
<P>
The new tax, however, would be effective only after the
minister of finance approves it, Rahardi said.
</P>
<P>
Export taxes on refined bleached deodorized (RBD) palm oil and
RBD palm olein were lowered to 8 percent from a previous 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
The government also slashed taxes on exports of crude palm
olein to 8 percent from 26 percent, crude palm kernel oil to zero
from 20 percent and RBD palm kernel oil also to zero from 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
It also reduced the export tax on prepackaged RBD olein not
exceeding five kilograms in volume to zero from 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
It lowered export taxes on crude stearin to zero from 15
percent and RBD stearin also to zero from 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The export taxes on crude coconut oil and RBD coconut oil
remained at zero.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, the world's second biggest producer of CPO, slapped
the levy on CPO and its derivatives after the rupiah nose-dived at
the onset of the financial crisis, making exports much more
profitable than domestic sales and leading to staggering shortages
of cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
Export tax on CPO was lowered to 30 percent early last month
from 40 percent in February and 60 percent in September last year.
</P>
<P>
The high export tax on CPO products has been widely criticized
specially after the rupiah strengthened to 8,000 rupiah against
the U.S. dollar late in May.
</P>
<P>
Many CPO producers have subsequently stopped their export
activities, adding more pressure to the already depressed local
market.
</P>
<P>
The government has estimated this year's CPO production at 6.9
million tons, or 2.8 million tons above domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
CPO production could reach 7.4 million tons in the year 2000
and 8.6 million tons in 2001, against a projected domestic demand
of 4.5 million and 5.1 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0171 </DOCNO>
