<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Send Peacekeeping Troops to Kosovo on Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's parliament issued a
statement Friday, allowing Ukrainian peacekeepers to be sent to
Kosovo, Yugoslavia, if NATO pays for the expenses.
</P>
<P>
The statement reaffirmed that Ukraine has advocated a peaceful
settlement of the Kosovo crisis since the very beginning and is
willing to take part in the U.N.-authorized international
peacekeeping mission in the war-torn Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
But the lawmakers said that the peacekeeping expenses of the
Ukrainian forces should be covered by NATO, which bombed
Yugoslavia for more than 11 weeks from March 24 to early June and
inflicted enormous losses on the Yugoslav people.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's troops should not be under the NATO command, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The parliament also expressed worries that the NATO-dominated
peacekeeping forces will not be able to prevent violence in Kosovo,
where such incidents have not ceased since NATO peacekeepers began
to be deployed in the middle of June.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was divided into five peacekeeping sectors dominated
separately by forces from the United States, Britain, Italy,
France and Germany under an agreement reached by NATO and Yugoslav
generals last month at the end of the war.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged the ukrainian government to prepare
proposals for the parliament to consider on deployment, including
the place, concrete tasks, number of troops and weapon equipment,
after discussions with the United Nations and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that 1,400 Ukrainian troops are ready to
head for Kosovo once the parliament and the president make the
final decision.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
