<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Network to Improve Nation's Re-employment Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 100 Chinese cities are
expected to be included in an unprecedented employment information
network by 2000, according a senior labor official.
</P>
<P>
Liu Danhua, an official with the Ministry of Labor and Social
Security, said that the network will serve 45 percent of China's
cities with populations of either more than one million or between
500,000 to one million, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
And all the involved cities, located in central and western
parts of China, are with considerable economic capabilities and an
active labor flow.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, employment agencies in the medium and large-
sized cities will be computerized by the end of this century,
which will enable at least 60 percent of employment information to
be available on the network.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, there were 35,449 employment agencies, 3.4
percent more than the previous year, among which 6,732 were run by
either non-governmental organizations or individuals, 14.8 percent
up than 1997.
</P>
<P>
Labor and Security Vice-Minister Lin Yongsan said at a press
conference that 3 million more workers are expected to be laid off
from State-owned enterprises by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
And related statistics show that the number of laid-off workers
in China by last April was 5.7 million, and the national
unemployment rate was 3.1 percent by the end of 1998. 
</P>
