<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Families Spend More on Child Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people are showing a
definite propensity to spend money on education, especially on
child education.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, the expenditures on education
for the average family in South China's Guangdong Province have
grown at some 12 percent annually for the last three consecutive
years.
</P>
<P>
And the per capita spending increased from 313 yuan (38 U.S.
dollars) in 1995 to 433 in 1998, which is higher than that of the
spending in entertainment and travels.
</P>
<P>
The money spent on child education mostly goes to tuition,
various fees and extracurricular training such as piano and art
courses.
</P>
<P>
Continuing education for Guangdong adults has also gained
popularity, with per capita spending reaching 58 yuan in 1998,
some 50 percent up than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Private schools are playing an important role in offering
educational opportunities in Guangdong, which have trained 2.6
million residents throughout the province since 1979. And some 230,
000 people attended private schools in 1998 in spite of the annual
tuition fees as high as several thousand yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Central government encourages enterprises or other
institutions to operate private schools so as to help provide more
opportunities for young people.
</P>
<P>
Major university have increased fees for their most popular
disciplines. For example, MBA majors in the South China University
of Science and Engineering will pay annual tuition and fees as
much as 10,000 yuan, with an additional 1,000 yuan for textbooks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
