<HEADLINE> More Sri Lankans Find Foreign Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-five thousand Sri Lankan
workers found employment abroad during the first six months of
1999, a 28-percent increase over the corresponding period last
year, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
There was a significant increase in Sri Lankans who found
employment in Saudi Arabia during the period, said L.K. Ruhunage,
Deputy General Manager of the Foreign Employment Bureau of Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Those employed in Middle East countries account for 80 percent
of the total while the remaining 20 percent found work in Greece,
Italy, Cyprus, the Maldives, South Korea, China's Hong Kong,
Seychelles and South Africa, Ruhunage said.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-nine percent of workers found jobs in Saudi Arabia, and
17 percent in Kuwait. In the meantime, 15 percent found jobs in
the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1.2 million Sri Lankans working abroad bringing
large amount of foreign exchange into the country. In 1998, Sri
Lankan migrant workers remitted back 60 billion rupees (880
million U.S. dollars), 60 percent of which were sent by house
maids. 
</P>
</TEXT>
