<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Percent of Forest Cover Down in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's forest cover is
dwindling at the rate of 50,000 per year, according to the latest
statistics by the Sri Lankan Forest Conservation Department (FCD)
here.
</P>
<P>
Today, the country's forest cover has dropped to almost 20
percent from the 70 percent recorded in 1990, the FCD said.
</P>
<P>
It also warns that if the denudation continues at this rate
unchecked, the time when the country will lose its entire forest
cover is not for away.
</P>
<P>
The rapid denuding of the country's forest cover was mainly to
the large-scale agricultural expansion and irrigation schemes, the
FCD pointed out that shifting cultivation has also contributed to
the degradation of forest cover.
</P>
<P>
Timber and other forest resources generate an income of 70
million U.S. dollars a year, and over 98 percent of rural energy
needs and 78 percent of those of the urban population are met from
firewood, according to the FCD.
</P>
<P>
The FCD called for greater public cooperation and public
involvement to protect the country's forest cover.
</P>
<P>
Measures such as the community participatory forestry program,
the massive forest conservation and management plan have been
taken to address the problem, but there is still the need to make
people aware of the disastrous consequences, the FCD added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
