<HEADLINE> Castro Returns to Cuba After Attending Rio Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro
returned here Friday from Brazil, where he attended the first
summit of Latin America, the Caribbean and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day summit early this week, the 72-year-old Cuban
president expressed strong support for economic cooperation with
the EU, which he said may well serve as a counterweight against
the U.S. influence in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
"It is better to have two or three major economic blocs than
just one," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban leader said the summit was "a good start" for Latin
Americans and Europeans to sit together to discuss trade and
investment without the U.S. presence.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the fact that the summit did not explicitly
condemn in its "Declaration of Rio de Janeiro" the U.S. Helms-
Burton law that hardened the U.S. embargo against Cuba. 
</P>
