<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Tolls to Remain Unchanged in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Panama Canal will keep the
present tolls after its restoration to the Panamanian sovereignty
in the year 2000, Alberto Aleman Zubieta, the interoceanic
waterway administrator, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Panamanian cabinet council has
approved the stability of tolls starting next January 1.
</P>
<P>
"However, it must be expected that as time goes, there will be
a need to increase the tolls, as it has been done in the last 85
years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Panama Canal Commission, a United States federal agency,
that will continue administering the waterway until December 31
this year, increased the tolls on seven occasions since 1914.
</P>
<P>
The canal official said that the waterway will obtain more
resources in the next century with the modernization of its
installations and the larger number of users.
</P>
<P>
"The international maritime cargo will continue prevailing in
the future and it is expected that in the next 40 years the cargo
moved along the canal will grow from 200,000 tons to 800,000 tons
a year," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Canal Administrative Authorities, total income
of the Canal reached 734 million U.S. dollars in 1998, including
545 million dollars of transit tolls. An average number of 36
ships passed though the Canal every day last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Systematic Deviations in Election: Indonesian Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Independent Committee for
Election Monitoring (KIPP) has concluded that there were no
systematic deviations in the June 7 election in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"Although there was a lot of problems and violations, there had
been no indication of systematic deceits or political engineering
during the elections," KIPP Secretary General Mulyana W. Kusumah
said.
</P>
<P>
Mulyana said the KIPP regarded the June election as fair and
free and would recognize the final vote count.
</P>
<P>
The committee however urged relevant law enforcement bodies
including the Supreme Court to investigate the violations and
deviations.
</P>
<P>
"The Supreme Court must take stern measures against all forms
of violations," Antara News Agency Saturday quoted Mulyana as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The KIPP has recorded 148,689 violations on voting day, in
which 84,950 cases disturbed the vote count process.
</P>
<P>
Mulyana said the irregularities were the result of often
unskilled human resources, the lack of law enforcement and the
lack of a campaign rules socialization program.
</P>
<P>
In its report, KIPP had also found three murder cases, 20 cases
of physical harm and 34 cases of violence during the elections.
</P>
<P>
The KIPP has also urged the General Election Commission (KPU)
and the National Elections Committee (PPI) to prioritize the vote
counting, as the two bodies would announce the election's final
results.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the PPI Jacob Tobing Friday said the PPI will start
national-level vote counting on July 6.
</P>
<P>
The PPI had previously planned to start the count on June 21
but was unable to meet this schedule because not all provincial
committees had submitted the results of their vote counts by then.
</P>
<P>
Tobing said the counting would be done in stages, starting with
returns from provinces that had already sent in vote count
tabulations and documents.
</P>
<P>
Out of 27 provinces, 12 provincial election committees had yet
to convey the results of their vote counts to the PPI because of
various problems such as the discovery of irregularities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Considering the fact that the KPU had until now not yet
finished the vote count, President B.J. Habibie Friday predicted
that the general meeting of the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR) -- originally set for late August -- will undergo a delay.
</P>
<P>
Habibie made the prediction at a meeting with a group of House
of Representatives (DPR) members at the State Palace here,
according to DPR Vice Speaker Abdul Gafur who led the
parliamentary delegation.
</P>
<P>
"August 29 (the date originally set for the installation of new
MPR members) will be impossible. He (the president) predicted it
will now take place by the end of September or early October,"
Gafur was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
At its forthcoming general meeting, the MPR will elect the
country's next president and vice president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
