<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs No Debt Relief Program: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia does not need a debt
relief program as it is not categorized as a highly-indebted poor
country, Coordinating Minister for Economic, Financial and
Industrial Affairs Ginandjar Kartasasmita said.
</P>
<P>
But rescheduling of Indonesia's foreign debts may be one of the
topics to be discussed at a meeting of the Consultative Group on
Indonesia (CGI) to be held in Paris later this month, Antara News
Agency Saturday quoted Ginandjar as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Indonesia had always been a good debt payer.
It was only in 1998 that it asked for a rescheduling of 4.5
billion U.S. dollars worth of debts.
</P>
<P>
At the CGI meeting scheduled for July 27-28, Indonesia would
request a rescheduling of an additional 2.6 billion to 2.7 billion
dollars in debts, Ginandjar added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, certain parties in the country proposed that the
government propose a debt relief program to the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and other donors as Indonesia's
foreign debt burden has already assumed worrying proportions.
</P>
<P>
According to Econit, an independent economic research
institute, Indonesia's foreign debts have reached a total amount
of 151.5 billion dollars, of which 67.4 billion dollars are
government debts and the rest private sector debts.
</P>
<P>
If Indonesia did not ask for debt relief, it would eventually
be unable to free itself from indebtedness, Econit researcher Arif
Arryman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that debt rescheduling would only be a temporary way
out that does not address the core of the problem.
</P>
<P>
A number of non-governmental organizations are also campaigning
for a debt relief program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
