<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Mission Leaves for EU to Negotiate Banana Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A Costa Rican delegation led by
Foreign Trade Minister Samuel Guzowski will leave here Sunday for
Brussels to negotiate the quotas of banana exports to the EU
market.
</P>
<P>
Guzowski said Friday that is an exploratory trip, and that he
will meet in Brussels with European Commission Vice President Leon
Brittan.
</P>
<P>
He said Costa Rica wants to know the European position on the
Central American bananas exports, after a World Trade Organization
(WTO) decision made it mandatory to change the quota system now in
force.
</P>
<P>
The present system favors Costa Rica, which supplies a little
more than 25 percent of that market.
</P>
<P>
Guzowski put forward a vigorous defense of the current
arrangement, although he admitted that the WTO decision requires
analysis of new possibilities.
</P>
<P>
"We want justice for Costa Rica, because we have signed an
agreement that must be respected," he said.
</P>
<P>
Several proposals are now on the table and Costa Rica prefers a
global quota system for all banana producing countries, under
which each one exports as much as it can.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed confidence in his country's
competitiveness in the world market. 
</P>
