<HEADLINE> Suleimanoglu to Prepare for Fourth Olympic Title Under Abadjiev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 2 (Xinhua) - Three times Olympic weightlifting
champion Naim Suleimanoglu of Turkey will prepare for the 2000
Olympic Games in Sydney under his first coach Ivan Abadjiev.
</P>
<P>
Suleimanoglu, who was born in Bulgaria, arrived here on
Thursday evening and will stay till Saturday. He used to compete
for Bulgaria but emigrated to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"I will train both here and in Turkey. After some ten days
Ivan Abadjiev will visit me in Turkey and then we will specify the
details of my training programme. I will take part in the Sydney
Olympics only if I decide I am well prepared," said Suleimanoglu.
</P>
<P>
"I will train here together with some of my major opponents. I
still do not know in which category I will compete," said
Suleimanoglu.
</P>
<P>
He will probably compete in the 62 kg category, where Sevdalin
Minchev of Bulgaria tops the world rankings, followed by Greek
Leonidas Sabanis and Nikolai Peshalov, a Bulgarian-born lifter
competing for Croatia.
</P>
<P>
"While he was training under me, Naim was a diligent and
disciplined athlete. Even though I do not have direct impressions
from his physical state at present, I know that he is training
regularly and I believe he has real chances of success in Sydney,"
said Abadjiev, head coach of Bulgaria's national team.
</P>
<P>
Suleimanoglu delivered to the Bulgarian coach another
invitation on the part of the Turkish federation to coach the
Turks, but Abadjiev once again declined.
</P>
<P>
"I have taken the commitment to prepare Bulgaria's national
team for the Sydney Olympics. I am not the kind of person who
goes back on his word," said Abadjiev.
</P>
<P>
Abadjiev coached the Turkish national team before the Atlanta
Olympics in 1996, in which Suleimanoglu and another Turkish
weightlifter Halil Mutlu, also born in Bulgaria, won the golds.
</P>
</TEXT>
