<HEADLINE> More Than 6,000 Dengue Cases Hit Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, HONDURAS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Honduran Health
Ministry registered more than 6,000 cases of common dengue and 47
of the hemorrhagic variety during the first semester of 1999, a
spokesman of the ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The classic dengue cases are 6,016, which is 1,906 more than in
the first semester of last year, according to the same source.
</P>
<P>
Dengue and other diseases of vector transmission has increased
in Honduras after the disaster caused by hurricane Mitch, since
the number of pools of stagnated and contaminated water had
increased.
</P>
<P>
The new rainy season also contributes to a bigger incidence of
dengue, malaria, cholera and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
The source said most of the 24 cases of hemorrhagic dengue,
which is fatal, were registered in Tegucigalpa. 
</P>
