<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayon Eruption Imminent, Warn Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' most active
volcano, Mayon, may erupt in the coming days or weeks, and the
country's disaster and relief agencies should beef up contingency
measures for an eruption, experts have warned.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology
(Phivolcs) said Friday that Mayon has showed signs of imminent
explosion and alert level two is being maintained.
</P>
<P>
Alert level two means the permanent danger zone around Mayon
has been extended from six kilometers to seven kilometers and
people within the danger zone should be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Prompted by the imminent explosion of the volcano, which is
about 330 kilometers southeast of Manila, the Albay provincial
disaster coordinating center hastened the evacuation of about
18,000 residents within the danger zone, according to a Manila
Standard newspaper report.
</P>
<P>
While the Education Department ordered Friday the suspension of
classes in schools within the vicinity of Mayon, Defense Secretary
Orlando Mercado ordered the pre-positioning in Albay of resources
like food supplies, transportation and manpower.
</P>
<P>
Mayon had a mild eruption on June 22 and the eruption only
lasted about 10 minutes. No casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
During the eruption, a high column of ash and smoke were seen
on Mayon's crater, but the volcano calmed down an hour after its
eruption.
</P>
<P>
Mayon, the most active volcano in the world, has erupted at
least 40 times since 1616. The volcano's eruption on February 2,
1993 killed 78 people and affected 17,119 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
