<HEADLINE> Man United Rules Out FA Cup Reprieve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Martin Edwards has dismissed any
possibility of Manchester United returning to next season's FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
The United chairman remains convinced that the club have no
option but to drop out of the Cup in order to participate in the
World Team Championship.
</P>
<P>
Sports Minister Tony Banks raised the possibility of United
taking part in the Cup as long as they competed in the inaugural
FIFA tournament in Brazil in January.
</P>
<P>
Banks is willing to consider any alternatives which are better
than the current proposal, but Edwards is adamant there will be no
reprieve.
</P>
<P>
United, Banks, the Football Association and the Premier League
spent weeks going through the various scenarios and Edwards claims
this is the only answer to the problem.
</P>
<P>
He insists the World Team Championship must take priority
because United do not want to damage England's 2006 World Cup bid.
</P>
<P>
"We have been through all this a thousand times and we have
looked at every single possibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There's no way we can fulfill our fixtures by competing in the
FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
"We need the FA Cup dates to catch up on our two league games
lost because of the World Team Championship.
</P>
<P>
"There's also the Sheffield Wednesday game, which has been
moved because of the World Club Championship in Tokyo. That makes
a total of three league games which we need to catch up on. If we
were involved in the FA Cup we would not be able to do this."
</P>
</TEXT>
