<HEADLINE> U.S. Lawmakers Urge Further Probe Into Embassy Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Some U.S. Congressmen said here
on Thursday that the United States should make further
investigation on the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade to
find out truth about the tragic event.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers made the remarks at a meeting with Chinese
Ambassador Li Zhaoxing on Capitol Hill Thursday morning. The two
sides exchanged views on the current Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congressmen expressed their willingness to advance the
U.S.-China relations, support the "One China" policy, and to make
continued efforts for furthering economic and trade ties with
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They voiced their "continuous and unconditional" support for
the renewal of China's Normal Trade Relations, and for the
country's access to the World Trade organization.
</P>
<P>
Some of the Congressmen also castigated the Cox report, saying
that there are "unfounded facts" and loopholes. The report also
treats the Chinese Americans "unfairly", they said, adding that
they will do as much as they can to prevent discrimination against
the Chinese Americans.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li reiterated that the bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade by the U.S.-led NATO forces is an event with
serious consequences, which violates China's sovereignty, hurts
the feelings of the Chinese people and derails the Sino-U.S.
relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the United States must whole-heartedly
recognize the seriousness of the event, bear all responsibilities
for it, continue the investigation, give a thorough clarification
of the truth of the matter, take those responsible to justice, and
pay adequate and effective compensation immediately to relatives
of those killed and to those wounded in the bombing as well as for
property damages of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, so that the
issue could be settled in a responsible way as seen by the Chinese
government and the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the issue of Taiwan is China's internal affairs, Li
urged the United States to abide by the three joint communiques
between the two countries as well as commitments it has made on
the issue, stop selling advanced weaponry to Taiwan, stand against
the consideration of the Taiwan Security Enhancement Act which
seriously interferes with China's internal affairs, so that new
damages to the Sino-U.S. relations could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li also refuted the Cox report, saying that the
report, fraught with fabrications and rumors, will go down in the
history of world diplomacy as a laughingstock and a record of
notoriety.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Cox report has undermined Sino-U.S. relations
and the U.S. side should take concrete measures to reduce its
negative impacts.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. Congress should do more that are beneficial for
Sino-U.S. relations, rather go in the opposite direction," said Li
at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
