<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AFOR Ready to Transport 2,000 Kosovo Refugees a Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- NATO forces in Albania (AFOR) are
ready to send 2,000 refugees back home a day in cooperation with
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), an AFOR
spokesman said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
AFOR's aim is to transport 2,000 a day, but this also will
depend on the actual situation on the refugees, said Colonel Helge
Eriksen.
</P>
<P>
Organized repatriations of Kosovo refugees in Albania started
on Thursday and first contingent of 500 people has been sent back
to Kosovo on the day.
</P>
<P>
Organized repatriations of Kosovo refugees sponsored by UNHCR
continued on Friday. AFOR and the Albanian military vehicles
carried some 1,800 Kosovars to Kukes from other parts of Albania
on the day, from where they will travel to Prizren, Pristina and
Urosevac in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on NATO's future plans in Albania, Eriksen said that
since an agreement has been signed between the Albanian government
and AFOR, AFOR will stay till its "humanitarian mission" in
Albania ends.
</P>
<P>
According to Albania's official statistics, there are some
170,000 Kosovo refugees remaining in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
