<DOCNO> XIE19990703.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes N. Ireland New Proposal (With more details) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Friday hailed an agreement reached by British and Irish prime
ministers on power-sharing cabinet in Northern Ireland, calling it
a "very welcome development."
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks at a photo session with visiting South
Korean President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged Protestants and Catholics in Northern
Ireland to support the plan to salvage the Good Friday peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the proposal has given peace a chance in the
British province.
</P>
<P>
"It gives us a chance to fulfill the Good Friday accords. It
gives the people of Northern Ireland, both Protestant and
Catholic, a chance to shape their destiny and govern
themselves," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It gives us a chance to put an end to guns and violence
forever...I think this is very, very important," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the British and Irish prime
ministers proposed that both Protestants and Catholics would
form an Ulster cabinet on July 15 and Irish Republican Army
disarmament started "within days."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it would give a good opportunity to resolve
difficult problems that had caused violent conflicts over
several decades in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Clinton added the United States supports the efforts made by
both British and Ireland in solving the difficult problem and it
will hold all the parties to their commitments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
